Done.
I also had to modify the code to use
const bool found = new_catalog_mgr->LookupNested(path, ...)
rather than
const bool found = new_catalog_mgr->LookupNested(rel_path, ...)
It seems as though MakeRelative() strips off any leading slash, while MakeRelativePath() inserts a leading slash. 
@jblomer Test 802 should now pass, and turns out to already test the ability to swap a nested catalog (that contains another nested catalog).  Do we still need a separate integration test?

I assume the timestamp difference arises because something needs to explicitly update the timestamp as recorded in the parent catalog to match the swapped-in nested catalog?

As far as I can tell, all of the existing code that handles this kind of thing does so by mounting the nested catalog and updating the root directory entry in the nested catalog to match the transition point directory entry in the parent catalog.  Since we're trying to avoid touching the new nested catalog, I'm assuming that we should do basically the reverse: get the root directory entry from the freely attached new catalog object, and use that to update the transition point directory entry in the parent catalog?
@jblomer Is this the correct approach?

Good catch! Yes, we forgot about updating the transition point in the parent catalog entry. It should work as you describe.

Updated - SwapNestedCatalog() now looks up the root directory entry from the freely attached new catalog object, and applies it using:
  dirent.set_is_nested_catalog_mountpoint(true);
  dirent.set_is_nested_catalog_root(false);
  parent->UpdateEntry(dirent, nested_root_path);
  parent->TouchEntry(dirent, xattrs, nested_root_path);
It seems to be necessary to use both UpdateEntry() and TouchEntry() - AFAICT the former is required to update the link count and the latter is required to update the extended attributes.
This now passes the updated test 802 and I have verified that the test code really is checking counters etc (by temporarily hacking out the call to PopulateToParent()).
